709505f-a.title: Manhattan: 6th Avenue - 43rd Street (West)
709505f-a.text:
Sixth Ave., north from West 43rd Street to Central Park, and showing
a general view northeast from the Bush Terminal Building (130 West 42nd
Street, south side, between Sixth Ave. and Broadway). This view taken
prior to the sudden building boom shows the Plaza Hotel, the Sherry
Netherland, the Ritz Tower, St, Patrick's Cathedral, the Collegiate Church
of St. Nicholas and B.F. Keith's Hippodrome (Sixth Ave., east side, between
West 43rd and 44th Streets). Also shown are the Queensboro and the Hellgate
R.R. Bridges.
May 1926.
Brown Brothers.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.

709507f-b.title: Manhattan: 6th Avenue - 43rd Street (West)
709507f-b.text:
Sixth Avenue, from West 43rd to 44th Streets, showing the low
buildings on the west side,as viewed across the former Hippodrome
site. The latter has become the parking lot shown. This occupies
the easterly frontage of the Avenue. Times Square and Broadway
are just beyond, distinguished by the dominant Paramount Building.
Vcrious hotels are on the side streets. Observable are the 44th
Street HHotel, the Hotel Langwell, the Peerless and the St James.
View 3 is northwestward towards W. 44th Street.
May 5, 1940
Views 1,2,3
P. L. Sperr
NO REPRODUCTIONS

709504f-b.title: Manhattan: 6th Avenue - 43rd Street (West)
709504f-b.text:
Sixth Avenue, east side, from West 43rd
to 44th Street's, showing prominently the old
Hlppodromme. This structure erected aboot 1912,
housed rany fammous productions, from pageants to
talking pictures. Famous artiats icluding Taderewski
hhave played here. In 1922, Richard Straus conducted a
series of concerts with the Philadelphia Orchestra. Prior
to its demolition in the Fall of 1939, tt was a motion
picture house. Vrious sport af'a'rs wore held here.
View 1: March 9, 1929
2: 'ay 27, 1930
3: May 1, 1933

709509f-a.title: Manhattan: 6th Avenue - 43rd Street (West)
709509f-a.text:
Sixth Avenue, west side, from West 44th (center) to 43rd
Streets. This photograph, taken from the east side of the Avenue
is in s southwestward direction to show towering structures at
42nd Street. They are the dominant Bush Building and the No. 113
W. 42nd 5treet Building.
View 2 is photographed across the parking lot where the former
Hippodrome stood. The low 6th Avenue buildings in this view are
at 43rd Street. To the left is a portion of Stern's Department
Store. The white 33-story, No. 1441 Broadway Building is included.
View 1: April 5, 1239
View 2: May 1940
P. L. Sperr
